T1  - Valuation of asset leasing contracts
AU  - McConnell, John J.
AU  - Schallheim, James S.
JO  - Journal of Financial Economics
VL  - 12
IS  - 2
SP  - 237
EP  - 261
PY  - 1983
DA  - 1983/08/01/
SN  - 0304-405X
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-405X(83)90037-5
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304405X83900375
AB  - This paper describes the relation among a variety of asset leasing contracts, including: (1) cancellable operating leases; (2) leases which grant the lesse an option to extend the life of the lease; (3) leases that grant the lessee an option to purchase the leased asset at a fixed price at the maturity date of the lease; (4) leases that grant the lessee the right to purchase the leased asset at its ‘fair market value’ at the maturity date of the lease; (5) leases that grant an option to the lessee to purchase the leased asset at a prespecified price anytime during the life of the lease; (6) leases that require the lessee to purchase the leased asset at a fixed price at the maturity date of the lease; and (7) leases that contain non-cancellation provisions. The paper uses a compound option pricing framework to develop a general model for valuing (or evaluating) each of the types of leasing contracts. Numerical examples are presented to illustrate the effect of the various elements of a leasing contract — including cancellation risk and residual value risk — on equilibrium rental payments.
ER  - 

